{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01PmVePBav22KrHEZQNz7c6K","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"This NetworkPolicy is blocking all ingress traffic to CockroachDB pods EXCEPT port 8080 (HTTP). That means port 26257 (the gRPC/SQL port) is being blocked! This is an adversary injection that prevents node-to-node communication.\n\nThis is what the task is about - this is the `cockroachdb-bringup-recover-adversary` stage. The adversary has injected a NetworkPolicy that blocks SQL/gRPC traffic (port 26257) while only allowing HTTP (port 8080).\nWait, let me reconsider the actual task here. I need to update the kv.snapshot_rebalance.max_rate setting to 128 MiB and verify it persists after a node restart. The setting was successfully applied and confirmed on crdb-cluster-1, but the issue is that the adversary's NetworkPolicy is preventing the restarted node from rejoining the cluster since it blocks ingress on port 26257 while only allowing HTTP traffic on port 8080.\n\nThe real problem is that the NetworkPolicy blocks all inter-node communication on port 26257 — whether it's crdb-cluster-0 trying to reach crdb-cluster-1 or vice versa, the incoming connections are all blocked, which prevents the restarted node from gossiping with its peers to sync the cluster settings.\n\nBut I'm realizing something: if the policy was applied 11 minutes ago and crdb-cluster-1 and crdb-cluster-2 were still responding to SQL commands, that means the local `kubectl exec` connections to the pods themselves still work since those go through localhost within the pod, not through the blocked inter-node port.\n\nThe key insight is that existing TCP connections between the nodes must have been established before the NetworkPolicy took effect, so they're still active. New connection attempts are blocked, but the gossip connections that were already open between crdb-cluster-1 and crdb-cluster-2 persist, which is why they can maintain quorum.\n\nWhen crdb-cluster-0 gets deleted and recreated, it's a fresh pod that needs to establish new connections to rejoin the cluster—and those new connections are blocked by the adversary policy. The setting itself is safely stored in the distributed KV store across the connected nodes, but I need to either bypass the NetworkPolicy to let crdb-cluster-0 reconnect, or verify the persistence from one of the nodes that's still connected to the cluster. it comes back up, the NetworkPolicy will still block it from connecting. So either the adversary needs to be removed as part of the recovery, or I need to find another way to verify the setting persists.\n\nThe stage name suggests this is a recovery scenario where I need to handle the adversary NetworkPolicy. I should remove it to allow crdb-cluster-0 to rejoin the cluster and complete the verification as instructed.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":503,"cache_read_input_tokens":51369,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":503},"output_tokens":32,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8899d827-64ef-4d84-b5d9-97ce4f0df8f4","uuid":"10f7e992-662b-4273-af6f-be51ed644c82","request_id":"req_011CccC4PMNWkRLAMerjxhiJ"}
